# Documentation standards (XMSTP)

## XMSTP is mandatory

All Markdown under `docs/` must comply with the [Extensible Manual of Style for Technical Publications (XMSTP)](https://github.com/aka-author/xmstp) on branch `dev`, including at minimum:

- `standards/structures/Generic_Requirements_for_a_Technical_Document.md` (GRTD)
- `standards/structures/General-Purpose_Information_Types.md` (GPIT)
- `standards/structures/Instructive_Content_Information_Types.md` (ICIT)
- `standards/langpacks/en/en-words.md` (project vocabulary)

When authoring or revising documentation, apply GRTD rules in practice:

- Introduce every table, figure, and extract in the paragraph directly above it (R.GRTD.0490–R.GRTD.0520).
- End enumeration introduction phrases with a full stop before parallel tables (R.GRTD.0950).
- Use one self-contained idea per sentence (R.GRTD.0340).
- Keep terminology consistent; define terms before use (R.GRTD.0220–R.GRTD.0580).
- Enumerate subjects before dedicated subsections when a section covers multiple subjects (R.GRTD.1060–R.GRTD.1100).
- Do not use bold for decoration; use it only where XMSTP or the target document genre requires emphasis.

Prefer *program* over *application* for the desktop executable (en-words: *application* is deprecated for PC users).

If project docs and XMSTP conflict on prose mechanics, XMSTP wins for prose mechanics. Product meaning still follows FS precedence.


## funcspec.md is hands-off

`docs/specs/funcspec.md` (FS) is written and owned by the user.

Agents must not edit, rephrase, restructure, or “sync” FS — even when techspec, arch, impl, or code appear inconsistent with FS.

If another document disagrees with FS, fix the other document or record a waiver in the appropriate target doc or `docs/verification/`. Never “correct” FS on the user's behalf.

Allowed for FS: read, cite, link, and explain. Not allowed without an explicit per-file FS edit request that also contains `Mutabor`: any write to `funcspec.md`.


## Document stack for win-cpp-qt

Precedence for product meaning:

1. `docs/specs/funcspec.md` (read-only for agents)
2. `docs/specs/techspec-win-cpp-qt.md`
3. `docs/specs/arch-win-cpp-qt.md` (informative)
4. `docs/specs/impl-win-cpp-qt.md` (as-built, informative)

When updating win-cpp-qt docs, keep techspec, arch, and impl mutually consistent. Do not duplicate FS prose into those files.
